  "exemplar_id": "ex_dvt_from_trauma_001",
  "frozen": true,
  "context_summary": "Middle-aged woman presenting with 3 days of right knee pain after slipping on the stairs. The pain is a dull ache, rated 6/10, worse with weight-bearing and better with rest. She now also reports pain and swelling in the right calf that started the day after the fall. No rash or obvious redness. She has high blood pressure and high cholesterol (on ramipril and a statin), a prior C-section, and no personal history of clots. The doctor has characterized the knee and calf pain and is moving into risk-factor questions.",
  "good_next_question": "Over the last couple of days with the leg pain, do you feel as though you've been immobilized?",
  "rationale": "This question probes for venous stasis from immobilization, the risk factor that converts a plausible post-traumatic calf injury into a deep vein thrombosis until proven otherwise. The presentation is anchored on a mechanical story (fell, knee hurts) and a novice clinician is likely to stay in the strain/sprain frame, but the calf swelling appearing a day after the injury, pain on palpation, and a slightly elevated temperature are warning signs that the calf finding may not be traumatic at all. Asking about immobilization tests the DVT hypothesis directly: a patient who has been resting and seated for days post-fall has been accumulating stasis, which combined with the swelling and the unilateral calf tenderness raises pretest probability enough to justify a Wells score and a compression ultrasound rather than treating it as a muscle strain. A positive answer (she has been staying seated and immobile) reframes the case toward DVT; a negative answer keeps gastrocnemius strain and ligamentous injury higher. Asking this beats further characterizing the knee pain because the calf finding, not the knee, is the dangerous thread to pull.",
  "tags": [
    "leg_pain",
    "middle_aged",
    "vascular",
    "unifying_hypothesis",
    "dvt",
    "risk_factor_probe"
  ],
